n><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 87<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/30/02 5:50:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=44.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   nuclear weapon physics, and the orion project</span><hr size=1> 1. Emp and incendiary effects: The higher the altitude of a<br>nuclear explosion the greater the area that will be exposed<br>to the emp, and heat pulse from the fireball.<br>All heat pulse and emp effects decline proportional to the inverse sqaure of the distance from the source of them<br>The maximium fire ignition radius is = to the sqaure<br>root of the yield in kilotons. This is the radius at which<br>all flammable materiels will be heated up to the mimimium temperature of 432 degrees farenheit sufficient to make<br>them burst into flame.<br>2. Nuclear blast effects, : The strength of the blast shockwave declines proportional to the cube root of<br>the yield measured in kilotons.<br><br>3. The method of core assembly determines the geometric shape of an atomic fission type device:<br>A single or double gun type atomic trigger wil be cylindrical.<br>A cylindrical core implosion device or a linear implosion device<br>will have also a cylindrical shape.<br> A qaudrouple gun trigger or other such  mutidirectional gun<br>trigger will have a wheel shape.<br>A spherical implosion fission device will have a sphere shaped<br>physics package . This is true whether a hollow core or solid core pit is used.<br>A multi-truncated-hollow cone : 2 dimensional implosion device will be a ball shaped core surrounded by a ring of explosive shaped charges:   or a cluster of explosive shaped charges  .<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 263<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/30/02 8:54:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=44.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: nuclear weapon physics, and the orion project</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 2 dimensional implosion device will be a ball shaped core surrounded by a ring of explosive shaped charges<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>I would think a ring-shaped core (essentially a short rod) would be preferred for a 2D gadget.<br>yale <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utmayes1999.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tmayes1999</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 89<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/2/02 4:23:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=44.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: nuclear weapon physics, and the orion project</span><hr size=1> There is one type of fission weapon core in which for example<br>a sphere of fissile material is made into 4 to 8 hollow cones.<br>These hollow cones are then wielded on  the inside   of a hollow tamper sphere, beteen the tamper and a solid spherical neutron source.Each fissile cone is backed by a shaped charge<br>of high explosive. When the explosive charges detonate <br>the fissile material cones are crushed onto the neutron source<br>by a two dimensional high explosive  shock wave. The cones then converge around the neutron source to form a common ball of critical mass. This is kinda like placing 4 aluminuim cans<br>together and then crushing all of then within a confined geometric space. When the cans are crushed close to each other they will merge together into one solid mass of crushed aluminium metal. This is the simpleest form of  the so called soccor ball configuration atomic pit. This is an advanced method of core assembly whose purpose is to make a small<br>lite weight, compact atomic weapon core.<br>Tim<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://members.hometown.aol.com/_ht_a/naturyl/images/YinYangsblack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 86<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/13/02 9:35:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=44.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Refueling Orion</span><hr size=1> Not sure where this shoud go, but it needed to be here, somewhere.<br><br> Reading through the book <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0060910305/qid=1021347608/sr=1-1/ref=sr_1_1/102-2249126-0504954">&quot;The Starship and the Canoe&quot;</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br> Dyson spoke about refueling an Orion (Brower wrote aabout Dyson's desire to find water in space, and how it's needed for life as well as rockets).<br><br> I was surprised to read that it's even a boon to an Orion; 90% of the mass of a pulse unit is the propellant! That can be water, or hydrogen, methane, ammonia, or a plastic compound. (Something to be vaporised by the bomb, to be shot towards the ship to impact the pusher plate to drive the ship forward. (Incidentally driving the final nail into the coffin of the notion that it's evaporating plate materials which provide the propulsive action/reaction)<br><br> Increase the performance estimates for an Orion driven ship, by remembering that the mass of future pulse units in a fraction of the final mass they need to be for use.<br><br>This turns some of my notions on their ears <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br> I wouldn't have thought that the pit &amp; structure were so small a portion of the bomblet mass.<br><br><br> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://members.hometown.aol.com/_ht_a/naturyl/images/YinYangsblack.gif" BORDER=0> at: 5/13/02 9:38:08 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utmayes1999.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tmayes1999</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 105<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/13/02 11:43:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=44.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Refueling Orion</span><hr size=1> That depends on what kind of design is applied to the<br>atomic  core mechanism  of a pu. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=cattlecar>cattlecar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 39<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/14/02 7:15:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=44.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Refueling Orion</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Incidentally driving the final nail into the coffin of the notion that it's evaporating plate materials which provide the propulsive action/reaction<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>According to Dyson's latest book, Project Orion, it is stated that the main propulsion is indeed from material carried along with the bomb and vaporized.  Also, that the explosions were shaped towards the pusher.  But, it did state that some unknown amount of the pusher plate would vaporize as well.  An unknown factor then and now is the interaction between the plasma from the bomb, and the plate evaporation.  It may be too unstable of a region for effective control when these two forces interact.<br><br>Maybe NASA will use modern 3D computer simulations that weren't available to the original Project Orion team in the 1960's to find out? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1140<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/14/02 8:13:53 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=44.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Refueling Orion</span><hr size=1> Still waiting on my copy of that book. The bookstore told me yesterday that it wasnt available for shipment until June! Oh well. Some of the older websites give a good historical account of propellant. At first they planned to keep the propellant (some kind of plastic) separate to the bomb itself. Discs were to be dropped behind bombs to be vapourised into plasma which then impacts the pusher plate. From a waste perspective this may seem more efficient but perhaps due to the added complexity of a cannon designed to fire off different projectiles, they abandoned this avenue to enclose the propellant into the bomb casing.<br>Pulse unit detonation was still a complex procedure though. the pusher plate was never a source of propellant. Quite the opposite view was taken. A graphite based paint was to be sprayed on to the plate between pulses to minimise wear and increase longevity. This sounds like a nightmare but the challenges were taken and feasibility was proven. Im certain that today, 2 generations later, another group could easily reproduce the results and finish the project. India for instance has no obligations to the nuclear club and has some of the best minds on the planet. they have produced some of the best mathematicians and physicists in history. I'm hoping they or another nation will take an interest in what the US has thrown away in haste.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=cattlecar>cattlecar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 42<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/14/02 8:23:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=44.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Refueling Orion</span><hr size=1> Man, Ive read my copy twice!  You should consider Amazon.com, or some other online book reseller. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://members.hometown.aol.com/_ht_a/naturyl/images/YinYangsblack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span>