s a dire emergency, such as an impending asteroid impact.  The needs of the many outweighing the needs of the few.<br><br>My vote would be to do as much computer simulation, testing, etc. as possible, and then actually build a ground launch capable Orion.  Break Glass in Case of Emergency type use.  It would stand ready to defend the Earth against annihilation from space.  Big rock meets fast moving little rock event.  <br><br>What would be the harm? <br><br>Maybe it would be seen as a doomsday weapon by other countries and start another arms race.  Good reason why it should be a multi-national endeavour.<br><br>Now, if a 'clean' bomb was developed, that would be a different ball game.  You would still have an enormous public relations battle on your hands though! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://members.hometown.aol.com/_ht_a/naturyl/images/YinYangsblack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 93<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/18/02 10:38:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=44.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   &quot;Break Glass in Case of Emergency&quot;</span><hr size=1> Yale wrote<br>&gt;&gt;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Either or both (relevant treaties) forever ban<br>the use of Orion-type propulsion<br>&gt;<br></i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->Cattlecar wrote<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> <br>&gt;I wouldn't use the word 'forever', as treaties are<br>by their very nature, transitory.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br><br> This is one thing I've been trying to understand from Yale. Who says treaties are forever immutable, unchangeable, etched deeply into erosion-proof stone? The treaties themselves quite clearly carry openings for revision or even unilateral withdrawal by any nation.<br> As well, any nation can back out of a treaty and do what they want. The only thing the others can do is economic sanctions (which mean nothing to the nation opening space up for it's citizens and businesses) or war (which means nothing to the nation opening up space factories to make city-busters from asteroidal metals).<br><br> We, in the space advocacy community, are specifically thinking of a (hypothetical, far-off misty-distant utopian) future where a space effort is in the offing, and large amounts of people in several nations (and more importantly in those nation's power structures) are involved and interested.<br>It could happen...<br><br> In such a future, there could very well be a movement to use the best tool for interplanetary travel invented by humankind.<br> Contrary to the greatest fears of staunch anti-nuclear activists, there could very well be a recognition among some of those in power that a (space-only, IMO)  use of Orion could very well slip past the interests of national sovereignty &amp; security as being no credible threat to anyone, and (gasp of agonized anguish) <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> nuclear explosives in space</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> could be allowed.<br><br>&gt;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  It would be a terrible idea to ground launch one<br>of those monsters, unless it was a dire emergency,<br>such as an impending asteroid impact. The needs of<br>the many outweighing the needs of the few.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br><br> Far better to have a fleet of them in continuous use, plying the routes as trade carriers. Building a huge ship under glass to launch only in a 1 in 10,000,000 chance isn't economically feasible even as a hobby for the builders.<br> Far better to build up experience using them in space, along with mass drivers, solar concentrator mirrors, NTRs, asteroid mine/retrieval bases, and space factories.