riment area (most of the time, anyway).<br><br>The overall point of this discussion is: Materials SURVIVED, test chamber bulkheads remained intact, there was no widespread &quot;vaporization&quot;, and where there WAS material vaporized from surfaces, those amounts were carefully measured.  Even with the cold X-ray tests -- you could re-enter the test chamber after a few weeks to collect the sample coupons.  (Notice my Posticon -- been there, done that <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .<br><br>That is what I did -- I instrumented samples, for things like temperature rise, material stress and strain, energy dissipation, acceleration and shock, etc.<br><br>So with the proper energy spectrum, in addition to the proper yield; and with the proper materials on the working side of the pusher plate, one can certainly minimize the loss of the pusher plate material.<br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=cattlecar>cattlecar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 175<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/21/02 9:43:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=44.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~macami/ez/spinthingie.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Loss of Material on &quot;Pusher Plate&quot;</span><hr size=1> Questions:  How did the test chamber itself stand up to repeated blasts?<br>Did a smooth surface become irregular (on a small scale), and wouldn't repeated <br>blasts on the same surface cause this irregularity to magnify afte